{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CZzhAfdA62SNdyoAfZTjHF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The `/api/photos` endpoint only supports a `before` cursor (not an `after` cursor). To implement gap-fill after reconnect, I need to either:\n\n1. Add an `after` parameter to the photos API endpoint, or\n2. Use the existing API in a different way\n\nLooking at the task description more carefully:\n> on reconnect, refetch latest photos since last known createdAt to fill any gap\n\nThe simplest approach that doesn't require modifying the backend would be to use a regular photos fetch and then filter/deduplicate on the client side. Since photos are sorted newest-first, I can fetch the latest photos (without any cursor) and then deduplicate against existing photos in the store. \n\nThe deduplication by id is already built in, so after reconnect I can just fetch the first page of newest photos and let the existing merge logic handle duplicates. There's a risk of missing photos if more than one page worth were created during downtime, but that's acceptable for a photo wall use case.\n\nTo be more thorough, I should add an `after` parameter to the photos API so I can fetch only photos created after the last one I saw, rather than relying on the page limit. Let me look at how the server's `listPhotos` function works to understand how to implement this properly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3188,"cache_read_input_tokens":42365,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3188},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ed868337-1ce4-4888-9c5a-71786f4d3f4e","uuid":"eb188b2a-ea00-417c-8047-95a14efa9524","request_id":"req_011CbRSGuptQUbz4MZzGPrfX"}
