{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VL5WJgqpQzKsqz1KLrZW26","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Progress! Most tests pass now. The gap-fill test fails because the gap-fill promise hasn't resolved yet after only 3 `Promise.resolve()` calls. The chain is likely deeper. Let me analyze:\n\nThe `gapFill` function calls:\n1. `fetchFn(photosUrl)` → returns a mock `Response` that is a `mockResolvedValue`. This resolves on the FIRST tick.\n2. `res.json()` → this calls `Response.json()` which is also async. Needs another tick.\n3. The `for` loop → synchronous after the data resolves.\n\nBut the Response object here is a native `Response`. \n\nI'm realizing the `mockResolvedValue` doesn't settle synchronously—it creates a Promise that settles on the next microtask tick, and then `res.json()` creates another Promise that also needs its own tick. So the chain requires at least two ticks: one for the fetch to resolve, another for the response body parsing to complete.\n\nSince the Response mock involves reading a ReadableStream, which could involve multiple async operations in Node.js, a few ticks might not be enough. Let me try adding more `Promise.resolve()` calls to ensure everything settles properly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1163,"cache_read_input_tokens":71395,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1163},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ed868337-1ce4-4888-9c5a-71786f4d3f4e","uuid":"6e3b9da2-6358-4cfa-8253-4c9bc0004a7f","request_id":"req_011CbRSfZnH1RejnY5utXSfF"}
